{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_juniper_ver01/data/2017236974/00279559009/1938012001/0084.xml":{"full_text":"Engraved Invitations Not Needed For\nWelcome Cooking School Party\n*_____\nInterest Spreads In The Herald's Free\nAnd Profitable Film Entertainment\nDue Feb. 3 And 4 Bn The\nImperial Theatre\nA welcome invitation to the wise\nis sufficient.\nEvidently The Roanoke Rapids\nHerald will not have to get out en\ngraved announcements for that re\nunion of homemakers Feb. 3 and\n4th in the Imperial Theatre.\nGood news does travel fast, par\nticularly when it is news of a gala\nparty for the community, with\ngifts, with quality entertainment,\ncheered by jollity and novelty, and\nspiced with knowledge\u2014all served\nhospitably by The Herald.\nNo door cards, coupons, printed\ninvitations, or cash will be needed:\njust the countersign of all alert\nhousekeepers, who are due to say\n\u201cShow me the latest home ideas,\u201d\nwrhen they advance on the Imperial\nat 10 a.m. Feb. 3rd and 4th.\nAll of the popular features of the\nformer Cooking School are here:\nThe free recipe sheets, the atmos\nphere of congenial informality, the\nwise counsel, the hints on clever\nshort-cuts, the up-to-the-minute\nsuggestions for entertaining, the\ndemonstration of delicious and\nnourishing dishes, the array of\nmodern kitchen equipment and the\ndistribution of daily gifts and real\nsurprises.\nAll those elements ot tun and\nprofit have been retained, and all\nare made doubly worth-while be\ncause every guest of The Herald\nwill have an individual close-up of\nevery process.\nThis scientific new laboratory\nof ideas has graduated out of the\nclass where hundreds of woinen\ncraned their necks in a vain at\ntempt to see what was happening\non the stage, or assailed the lectur\ner with plaintive cries: \u201cHold it up\nhigh, where we all can see.\u201d\nNow the camera will make the\ncourse truly fascinating and valu\nable, with remarkable close-ups of\neach process in a series of model,\nconveniently equipped kitchens;\nreal, workable kitchens (not the\nsynthetic, false-front variety),\nwhere trained homemakers will\nplan, measure, blend, mix and com\nplete appetizing cakes, pies, salads\nand meat dishes that look as\nthough they could be picked right\nout of the picture and eaten on the\nspot.\nAnd the camera has assembled\nall that sound information\u2014not as\na routine lecture, not as a formal\n\u201chighbrow\u201d demonstration, but as a\nreal Romance of Homemaking, full\nof suspense and charm, and infor\nmal chats from-one-good-cook-to\nanother.\nWhat about the story and what\nabout the cast?\nSome familiar Hollywood faces\nwill be recognized in this produc\ntion, which was filmed and direct\ned in one of the famous West\nCoast studios. The heroine i# a\nwinsome bride, who shares the per\nplexities of many an older house\nkeeper. Actually the title should\nbe \u201cIt Might Happen Here,\u201d for the\nhuman story has universal appeal.\nAnd it might have happened right\nin this community.\nNumerous nationally known\nfirms and progressive merchants\nfrom our own community are join\ning with The Herald in making the\nentertaining school available. They\npromise a daily harvest of generous\ngifts and surprises, which will be\ndistributed in addition to the use\nful recipe sheets.\nGuests of The Herald will share\na host of new adventures Feb. 3rd\nand 4th at the Imperial Theatre.\nThe bell will ring at 10 a.m. so be\non hand promptly.\nSo. Rosemary\nCounty Club\nMeets Jan. 12\nThe South Rosemary Home Dem\nonstration Club held the January\nmeeting Wednesday the 12th in the\nhome of Mrs. J. E. Tickle.\nThe meeting was opened by sing\ning \u201cThe Installation Song\u201d, then\nrepeating \u201cThe Collect\u201d. After a\nshort business session Mrs. Wheel\ner, County Agent, gave a most in\nteresting and helpful talk on\n\u201cKitchen Arrangement\u201d.\nMembers attending the meeting\nwere Mesdames M. E. Faison, V.\nC. Carter-Putney, B. C. Pair, R. L.\nPowell, C. W. Cooke, Robt. Frueler,\nC. T. Johnson, J. E. Tickle. Sam\nHockaday, L. A. Daniel, Carl Mur\nray, W. T. Pridgen, M. T. Whitley,\nand Miss Mertie Faison.\nHandy Harris\nA Christmas eve ceremony unit\ned in marriage Miss V. Ella Harris\nand Walter Roscoe Handy, both of\nGreensboro, Friday at 3 o\u2019clock at\nGrace Methodist Protestant\nChurch. Rev. J. Elwood Carroll,\npastor, heard the marriage vcpvs.\nWedding music was provided by\nMrs. Randolph E. Morrissett, or\nganist. The couple entered the\nchurch together unattended. The\nbride wore a wedding gown of Wal\nlis blue velvet, fashioned princess\nstyle with short train. Her small\noff-the-face hat was of the same\nmaterial and she carried a spray\nof yellow tea roses and valley\nlilies. For travel she changed to\nan ensemble of black worsted fea\nturing tailored simplicity. Her\nblouse was of white satin and she\nused black accessories. Over her\nsuit she wore a coat of black pony\nskin. Mrs. Handy was graduated\nfrom the Central Carolina Train\ning School, Sanford. She is the\ndaughter of Mrs. Vivian Shearin\nHarris, of Littleton, and the late\nJames Richard Harris. For eight\nyears she has made her home in\nGreensboro, having been connected\nwith the Greensboro Nursing Coun\ncil for the past year and previously\nwith Sternberger hospital and Dr.\nMarion Y. Keith\u2019s office. The\nbride-groom is the son of T. S.\nHandy, of North Wilkesboro, and\nis with the Corkran Packing House\nof Baltimore, Md., with headquar\nters in Greensboro, where he has\nlived for eight years.\nAfter a short wedding tr^p Mr.\nand Mrs. Handy will be at home\nnext week at 670 Chestnut Street.\nFormal announcements which read\nas follows are being issued: \u201cMrs.\nJames Richard Harris, of Little\nton, announces the marriage of her\ndaughter, V. Ella, to Walter Roscoe\nHandy Friday, December 24, 1937.\nAt home, Greensboro, North Caro\nlina.\nOut-of-town guests here for the\nwedding included Mrs. Clarence\nBrown and Mrs. M. L. Blevins, both\nof Winston-Salem, sisters of the\nbridegroom; Miss Of fa Lou Harris,\nof Littleton, student at Greensboro\nCollege, sister of the bride; Mrs.\nJ. R. Harris, of Littleton, mother\nof the bride; Miss Estelle Harris,\nof Norfolk, Va.; Mr. and Mrs. S.\nR. Jenkins, of Weldon; Miss Juan\nita Amick, of Washington, D. C.;\nMr. and Mrs. G. L. Amick, of Bur\nlington; and Miss Rachel McKenzie\nof Winston-Salem.\nMiss Hattie O\u2019dell spent the\nweek-end in Norfolk, Virginia.\nGarden Dept.\nElect Officers\nC'mmittees\nThe Garden Department of the\nRoanoke Rapids Woman\u2019s Club\nheld the regular monthly meeting\nJan. 17th in the home of Mrs. A. O.\nGeorge with Mrs. George and Mrs.\nR. M. Pope as hostesses.\u2014\nA business session was held be\nfore the regular program. Mrs.\nDot Bennett presented by-laws and\nconstitution, which had been pre\npared by a committee; these were\nunanimously accepted. Mrs. Wyche\ncalled attention to the projects of\nthe club, namely: sharing our flow\ners with the sick and to help land\nscape grounds at new school build\ning. Reports were made on flow\ners already donated. Mrs. C. E.\nMatthews was appointed to collect\nshrubs and plants to be given\nVance Street School.\nThe following officers were elect\ned for the new year: Mrs. C. A.\nWyche, chairman; Mrs. A. Meikle,\nco-chairman; Mrs. Dot Bennett,\nsecretary; Mrs. L. W. Clements,\ntreasurer; and Mrs. C. E. Matthews\ncustodian of papers.\nThe following committees were\nappointed, advisory committee for\nflower show: Miss Susan Holliday,\nMesdames J. R. Manning, W. A.\nWolhar, and Mrs. Clark; program\ncommittee: Mesdames C. E. Mat\nthews, D. C. Clark and Sam Bunn.\nThe program was opened with\nthe reading of a poem, \u201cThe Snow\ndrop\u201d from the year book by Mrs\nWyche. Mrs. Dot Bennett gave an\ninteresting paper on \u201cWinter and\nSpring Flowering Bulbs\u201d, which\nwas followed by a paper on \u201cAll\nSeason Fragrance\u201d by Mrs. L. W.\nClements.\nAt the conclusion of the program\na delicious salad course was served\nby the hostesses.\nMisses Bernice Hitchens, Ruth\nand Viola Glover spent the week\nend in Raleigh.\n\"Old World Charm on\na Modern Table,\" with\nCHANTILLY\nInspired by the celebrated Chateau of Chantilly, that superb\nexample of Louis XV art situated twenty-five miles from Paris, this\npattern has through two-score years won the affection of America\u2019s\nprominent brides.\nAppealing strongly to lovers of decorated patterns, Chantilly\ncreeps constantly upward in favor. While its oxidized adornment\ngains color as it ages, its plain, cushioned surfaces acquire greater\nlustre.\nWe believe you will like this new STERLING and invite your\ninspection of our complete stock of it this very week-end.\nLAND BROS.\nROANOKE RAPIDS and EMPORIA\nLEGGETTS\nANNOUNCE\nJAN. SALE\nAnnual Merchandising\nEvent Will Start\nFriday Morning\nLeggett\u2019s Department Store an\nnounces the opening of their An\nnual January Clearance and Sale\nof White beginning Friday morn\ning, January 21st, at 9 A.M., in a\nfour-page display advertisement in\nthis issue of the Herald, plus\nthousands of large 4-page, 24x36\nhandbills distributed over the wide\nterritory served by the store.\nOriginal exponents of the \u2018\u2018Jan\nuary Sale of White\u201d idea in Roa\nnoke Rapids, Leggett\u2019s has seen\nthis event grow in importance\nfrom year to year until they might\nbe well credited with changing\nthe buying habits of the territory.\nIn line with the policy of the over\n135 Belk stores operating in the\nSouth, of which organization Leg\ngett\u2019s is affiliated, the local store\nregularly features extremely low\nprices on white cotton goods at\nthis season of the year, and the\nevent is anxiously awaited by hun\ndreds of housewives served by the\nstore.\nIn addition, Leggett\u2019s feature low,\n\u201cclearance\u201d sale prices in all de\npartments.\nH. S. Loy, local manager of Leg\ngett\u2019s, was very optimistic over the\nprospects for their January Sale,\nas well as the business outlook as\na whole for the year 1938, when\ninterviewed the first of the week.\nAnticipating the largest sale of its\nkind ever held in Roanoke Rap\nids, Mr. Loy explained that their\ngreat corps of buyers had searched,\nthe large wholesale markets for ex\ntra values to offer their, customers\nfor the January merchandising e\nvent. \u201cWith mills all over the coun\ntry on short time we\u2019ve been able\nto buy goods at amazingly low\nprices,\u201d Mr. Loy said, \u201cand we are\npassing these values along to our\ncustomers in every instance.\u201d\nBesides the usual large and com\npetent force of salespeople regular\nly on duty at Leggett\u2019s, extra sales\nhlep will be called in to take care\nof the week-end crowds.\nDunn Saunders\nMr. and Mrs. James Harvey\nSaunders, of Enfield, N. C., an\nnounce the marriage of their\ndaughter, Ruby Elmo Saunders, to\nT. Burton Dunn Jr., of Fredericks\nburg, Virginia. The ceremony was\nsolemnized in the Chelsea Presby\nterian Church, in the Borough of\nManhattan, New York City, by the\nRev. Thomas Harvey Whilpley,\nTh. D., on December 3, 1937. Mrs.\nDunn attended the School of Nurs\ning at Roanoke Rapids, N. C., and\ngraduated in nursing on January\n15, 1937. And since graduating she\nhas been employed by the Mary\nWashington Hospital in Freder\nicksburg, Va., as a surgical nurse.\nThe groom is a member of a prom\ninent Virginia family; receiving his\neducation at the University of Vir\nginia, Bridgewater College, Vir\nginia Polytechnic Institute and The\nSoutheastern University School of\nLaw. Mr. Dunn is also prominent\nin politics; in both, Virginia and\nhigher ranks of the Democratic\nParty. Mr. and Mrs. Dunn are re\nsiding in their home in Petersburg,\nVa., where they are receiving con\ngratulations and good wishes of\ntheir many friends and relatives.\nMiss Lucy Perkinson of Hobgood\nwas the guest of Mrs. Wilmer Col\nlier Saturday.\nMrs. D. L. Wheeler left Wednes\nday for Gainesville, Fla. She was\naccompanied by Mrs. R. L. Apple\nwhite and Mrs. S. M. Gary of Hali\nfax.\nGeo. Cook of Warrenton was a\nvisitor in the city Saturday.\nDo You Have a Security Plan?\nTo save is commendable! But to save with a purpose often makes\nthe difference between successful progress and slipshod saving.\nA Security Fund for your wife and children in addition to life\ninsurance for protection will give them more happiness in the end\nat less cost to you! Try our systematic savings plan with $5 or\n$10 a month\u2014and have this extra financial protection for your\nfamily.\nIT PAYS TO SAVE\nREGULARLY!\nCome In And Let Ifs Explain Our Plan\nThe Roanoke Rapids\nBuilding Loan Assoc.\n10 W. 2nd St. F. J. Hawley, Secretary\n--t-1","height":"20960","width":"15272"}}
